Under the assistance of the Secretary for Financial Affairs and Treasury, the Financial Secretary oversees the maintenance of a stable and sound financial system, as well as policies aimed at preserving Hong Kong's status as an international financial centre. To implement these policies, the Chief Executive of the HKMA is responsible for:
- Promoting the overall stability and effective operation of the banking system;
- Collaborating with relevant authorities and organizations to develop the debt market;
- Managing matters relating to the issuance and circulation of legal tender notes and coins;
- Enhancing the safety and efficiency of financial infrastructure by developing payment, settlement, and clearing systems, and operating them when necessary; and
- Cooperating with relevant authorities and organizations to foster confidence in Hong Kong's currency and financial system, and implementing appropriate market development initiatives to strengthen Hong Kong's competitiveness in financial services globally.

The monetary base (Table 1) comprises:
- Certificates of Indebtedness (fully supporting banknotes issued by the three authorized banks);
- Circulating notes and coins issued by the Government;
- Total settlement balances held in the Hong Kong Monetary Authority's (HKMA) accounts (i.e., total reserves); and
- Foreign Exchange Fund bills and bonds issued by the HKMA on behalf of the Government.

The HKMA's Fintech Promotion Office continues working with banks to implement the Fintech 2025 strategy promoting widespread adoption of fintech solutions and enhancing Hong Kong's position as an Asian fintech hub. Major initiatives implemented during the year included:
- Promoting RegTech applications and conducting fintech application assessments;
- Advancing wholesale-level central bank digital currency (CBDC) work to improve cross-border payments;
- Deepening research on retail-level CBDC (e-HKD) issuance in Hong Kong;
- Launching the Business Data Link initiative;
- Strengthening talent development;
- Utilizing resource policies to support the fintech ecosystem;
- Enhancing cross-border fintech collaboration; and
- Promoting wider adoption of the Fast Payment System (FPS).

The Exchange Fund Advisory Committee has set the following investment objectives for the Exchange Fund:  
(i) Preserving capital;  
(ii) Ensuring that the overall money supply is fully supported at all times by highly liquid US dollar assets;  
(iii) Guaranteeing sufficient liquidity to maintain monetary and financial stability; and  
(iv) Seeking investment returns to the maximum extent possible within the parameters of the above (i)-(iii) to protect the long-term purchasing power of the Exchange Fund.

The responsibilities of the Risk Committee include:
- Identifying potential risks and threats faced by the HKMA and formulating strategies to mitigate their impact;
- Reviewing the current risk management systems within departments, identifying potential gaps and material risks, and ensuring appropriate measures are in place to address them;
- Establishing uniform risk assessment criteria and methods, and prioritizing resource allocation based on identified risks; and
- Promoting and strengthening a risk management culture within the HKMA, driving appropriate delegation and oversight.

During the audit conducted in accordance with the Audit Office's audit standards, I will apply professional judgment and maintain professional skepticism. I will also:
- Identify and assess the risks of material misstatement in the financial statements arising from fraud or error; design and perform audit procedures to address these risks; and obtain sufficient and appropriate audit evidence as the basis for my opinion. Because fraud may involve collusion, forgery, deliberate omission, false representations, or circumvention of internal controls, the risk of not detecting material misstatements arising from fraud is higher than that from error;
- Understand the internal control relevant to the audit to design appropriate audit procedures. However, this does not constitute an opinion on the effectiveness of the Group's internal controls;
- Evaluate whether the accounting policies adopted by the Chief Executive are appropriate, and whether the accounting estimates and related disclosures are reasonable;
- Determine whether the use of going concern as the basis of accounting by the Chief Executive is appropriate, and based on the audit evidence obtained, determine whether there are significant uncertainties relating to events or conditions that might cast doubt on the Group's ability to continue as a going concern. If I believe there are significant uncertainties, it is necessary to draw the attention of users to the relevant disclosure in the financial statements. If the relevant disclosures are insufficient, I must issue an auditor's report with a qualified opinion. My conclusions are based on the audit evidence obtained up to the date of the auditor's report. However, future events or circumstances may cause the Group to be unable to continue as a going concern;
- Evaluate the overall presentation, structure, and content of the financial statements, including disclosures, and whether the financial statements present fairly the transactions and events;
- Obtain sufficient and appropriate audit evidence regarding the financial information of entities or business activities within the Group to form an opinion on the financial statements. I am responsible for directing, supervising, and performing the group audit. I bear full responsibility for my audit opinion.
